default4.default              defaultHas enough been done to ensure the integrity of crime data? What more should be done?default&#xa0;default4.1
default              
defaultThere has been a long history of activity aimed at improving the integrity of crime data. The following chronology illustrates some of these events:
default&#xa0;
default1998 – 2005 - defaultNCRS and HOCR implemented and embedded.
default&#xa0;
default2003 – 07 - defaultAudit Commission conduct annual review of crime data.
default&#xa0;default2009 - defaultHMIC publish ‘Crime Counts’ (an inspection of violent crime recording) stating most violent crime is being recorded correctly by police but some victims may have been denied the service they deserve because their allegations were not recorded as crimes.
default&#xa0;
default2011 - defaultNational Statistician’s Review of Crime Statistics for England and Wales published, with eight recommendations to improve confidence and understanding of crime statistics.
default&#xa0;default2011 - defaultCrime Statistics Advisory Committee inaugurated on recommendation of the National Statistician.
default&#xa0;
default2012 -default Responsibility for reporting and publication of Crime Statistics moved to the ONS by the Home Secretary to create greater independence.
default&#xa0;
default2012 -default HMIC publishes ‘The Crime Scene’, examining how the police record, investigate and resolve crimes and incidents of anti-social behaviour.
default&#xa0;
default2012 -default ‘Action Fraud’ empowered to directly record from the Public and financial institutions. 
default&#xa0;default2013 - defaultHMIC data integrity inspections due to commence
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default4.2
default              
defaultThere is again some variance in processes across the country, making it difficult to be conclusive about the integrity of crime data. However, responses from Forces across the country suggest the following actions could help improve data integrity:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default5.default              defaultTo what extent can policy-makers have confidence in the statistics which result from the recording of crime by police forces?default&#xa0;default5.1
default              
defaultMost forces and their FCRs have a high level of confidence in their statistics, particularly for lower volume and high risk crimes and the majority believe that at the National Level there could be confidence in the statistics. The HMIC Data Integrity Inspection will hopefully assist in explaining this. 
default&#xa0;
default5.2
default              
defaultIssues that were raised that might create doubt were:
default&#xa0;
default5.3
default              
defaultPrior to the introduction of HOCR and NCRS, the ONS found that the volume of police recorded crime (in comparable categories) was between 50-62% of the total estimated from the British Crime Survey (BCS). This suggested a large volume of crimes were not being recorded. The gap between the volume of police recorded crime and BCS crime narrowed substantially around the time of NCRS introduction. From 2002/03 the ONS found the volume of police recorded crime (in comparable categories) rose to around 90% of the BCS total and remained there until 2007/08.  
default&#xa0;
default5.5
default              
defaultHowever, from 2007/08 onwards there was a sharper fall in police recorded crime than BCS crimes. The effect of this was to increase the difference between the volume of police recorded crime and BCS crime. This trend continued until 2011/12, when the volume of police recorded crime (in comparable categories) was just under 70% of that reported to the Crime Survey (Source- Analysis of Variation in Crime Trends, ONS, Jan 2013).    
default&#xa0;
default5.6
default              
defaultIn 2012/13, crime reported to the Crime Survey of England and Wales (CSEW) fell at a sharper rate (7%) than crime reported to the police (5%), suggesting that the figures are converging.  (NB-The CSEW replaced the BCS in 2012).
default&#xa0;
default5.7
default              
defaultThe ONS report ‘Analysis of Variation in Crime Trends’ (2013) suggested drivers for the divergence between CSEW/BCS crime and police recorded crime might include;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default6.default              defaultShould recorded crime statistics be classified as National Statistics?default&#xa0;
default6.1
default              
defaultAlthough there was recognition that this may be difficult to achieve due to inconsistencies across forces, the vast majority of responding forces agreed that Crime Statistics should be classified as national statistics
default 
defaultto provide greater confidence that the figures were true and accurate and to enhance their credibility and integrity. 
